Motivation

[source]

In 2017, Baltimore put out a city-wide call asking for Baltimore residents to avoid having any murders through quarterly Ceasefires and Peace Challenges (February, May, August, and November). This became known as Baltimore Ceasefire 365.

Imagine you are a data scientist working for the city of Baltimore where you help government officials implement and evaluate policies rolled out by looking and analyzing data. Recently, you have been contacted by Monica Valdes Lupi, the Executive Director from the Boston Public Health Commission who is interested in exploring the idea of implementing a similar city-wide ceasefire call in Boston to reduce gun deaths. She wants to know

  • Do the Baltimore ceasefires lead to a reduction in gun-related murders? Can you quantify any change in gun-related deaths during ceasefire weekends?

  • Is this a city-wide call you would recommend Boston implement in their own city? Is there any data that would suggest that such a policy would or would not be effective in Boston?

  • Is there anything else that should be considered before making any decision about this policy?

In this homework assignment, you will be exploring these questions, summarizing your results, and giving a final recommendation to Monica.

Helpful hints: You will find the Open Baltimore data useful for obtain crime data on shootings or homicides with a firearm.

Analysis

Baltimores first Ceasefire Weekend took place in August 2017. Since then, every Friday, Saturday, and Sunday on the 1st weekend of the month in February, August, and November and Mothers Day weekend (Friday, Saturday, and Sunday) in May has been denoted a Ceasefire Weekend. This adds up to a total of nine Ceasefire Weekends as of Oct 30, 2019. The dates of the past Ceasefire Weekends are listed below:
August 4-6, 2017
November 3-5, 2017
February 2-4, 2018
May 11-13, 2018
August 3-5, 2018
November 2-4, 2018
February 1-3, 2019
May 10-12, 2019
August 2-4, 2019

To analyze the impact of the ceasefires, I obtained Baltimore homicide data from: https://data.baltimorecity.gov/Crime/Homicides-2013-Present/33zm-qy8h. This analysis uses data downloaded on 10/30/2019, which contains 1,802 observations.

# load R packages

# load data
data <- read_csv("Homicides_2013_-_Present.csv")

The first step in the analysis is quantifying changes in gun-related deaths during Ceasefire weekends. To prepare the data for this analysis, I retained only records of homicides that were committed by firearm (N = 1,558 observations). Counts of gun-related homicides per day were tallied. Next, counts of gun-related homicides during Ceasefire weekends (dates listed above - total of 9 weekends) and during non-Ceasefire weekends (all other consecutive Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays after the first-ever Baltimore Ceasefire Weekend - total of 117 weekends) were tallied. Distributions of these counts are displayed with histograms. As can be seen, the distribution of homicide counts during non-Ceasefire weekends is slightly right-skewed, with one or two gun-related murders occurring most of these weekends. It is also the case that during most of the Ceasefire weekends only one or two gun-related murders occur. Because we have seen that the count data do not follow normal distributions and the sample size of Ceasefire weekends is small, assumptions of the t-test are violated. Thus, instead, I chose to use the Wilcoxon rank-sum test, which is a nonparametric test, or in other words the test does not assume that the data arise from a particular distribution. The Wilcoxon rank-sum test did not indicate that the change in murder counts was statistically significant at a significance level of 0.05.

Next, I wondered whether the Ceasefire events had a larger ripple effect. That is, do the reductions in gun-related deaths on Ceasefire weekends carry over to other days where no Ceasefire events are being held. To investigate this, I looked at the time period post the first-ever Ceasefire event (date indicated by orange line) and the same time frame (812 days) prior to the first-ever Ceasefire event (starting date indicated by blue line), and the time series plot suggests that overall counts of gun-related deaths did not change by much. An examination of the murder counts shows that there was an overall 4.2% reduction in murders, with the weekends experiencing a 7.7% reduction and the weekdays experiencing a 1.7% reduction. Again, we see that the distributions of daily murder counts both pre and post the first-ever Ceasefire event are not normal, but are similar in shape, so a Wilcoxon rank-sum test was used to compare the distributions, and test results indicated that the change in murder counts was not statistically significant.

To judge how a similar Ceasefire policy would work in Boston, we need to investigate differences in the two cities. Boston crime incidents data was obtained from: https://data.boston.gov/dataset/crime-incident-reports-august-2015-to-date-source-new-system. The dataset contains records of crime incident reports in Boston from July of 2015 to date. However, according to the website, starting October 2019, this data set will not update until further notice due to system maintenance. Thus, the dataset used for this analysis contains data up to September of 2019. To compare the two cities, Baltimore homicide reports from the same time frame, July 2015 to September 2019, were used.

A time series plot of homicides in the two cities shows that neither city has experienced a drastic change in homicide counts since July of 2015, and Boston consistently has fewer homicide cases than Baltimore. Histograms of monthly homicide counts in both cities show that the counts are approximately normally distributed, so a t-test can be used to determine if the monthly means of gun-related murders in the two cities (24.6 in Baltimore and 4.4 in Boston) are significantly different from each other. Test results indicated that the difference was statistically significant, and a 95% confidence interval of the difference was given as (18.4, 22.0).

Next, I looked at whether the murders were distributed over the week differently in the two cities. The plot below suggests that homicides are distributed more evenly over the week in Baltimore, while in Boston most of the homicides occur on Saturday. To more quantitatively assess this observation, I constructed a Quasi-Poisson regression model for each of the two cities where daily gun-related murder counts were regressed over indicator variables representing the days of the week. The model for Baltimore showed that the number of daily murder counts does not depend on the day of week. The model for Boston showed that the number of daily murder counts is significantly higher on Saturday compared to the reference day of Monday. The choice of the Quasi-Poisson model was based on the fact that there was over-dispersion in the data - the variance of the counts was larger than the mean.

BaltimoreWeekOfDay$Freq <- BaltimoreWeekOfDay$Freq/sum(BaltimoreWeekOfDay$Freq)

# distribution in Boston

Summarize your findings here.

Comparison of gun-related murders on Ceasefire weekends and non-Ceasefire weekends since August 4, 2017 (start date of first-ever Baltimore Ceasefire weekend) showed that there was a reduction in murder counts during Ceasefire weekends. On average, 1.44 gun-related murders occurred during Ceasefire weekends, while 2.03 occurred during non-Ceasefire weekends. The 95% confidence interval of the change in murder counts was (-1.19, 0.01). The Wilcoxon rank sum test indicated that this change was not statistically significant. Comparison of gun-related murders during the time period after the first-ever Baltimore Ceasefire weekend (August 4, 2017 - October 24, 2019) and the time period prior to the event (May 15, 2015 - August 3, 2017) showed that there was only slight reduction in overall murder counts.

Comparison of gun-related murders in Baltimore and Boston indicated differences between the two cities in murder counts and patterns. Far fewer number of homicides occurred in Boston compared to Baltimore. In addition, homicides are distributed more evenly over the week in Baltimore, while in Boston most of the homicides occurred on Saturday.

Add your response here

In considering a similar city-wide ceasefire call in Boston, it is important to first consider whether the original city-wide ceasefire call in Baltimore has been effective. Baltimores first Ceasefire Weekend took place in August 2017, and since then, a total of nine Ceasefire Weekends have been called. Analysis of homicide data in Baltimore after August 2017 showed that on average, 1.44 gun-related murders occurred during Ceasefire weekends, while 2.03 occurred during non-Ceasefire weekends. The 95% confidence interval of the change in murder counts was found to be (-1.19, 0.01). These findings show that during ongoing Ceasefire Weekends, there is a moderate reduction in gun-related murders. A further examination of homicide trends in the 27 months (812 days) before and after the first-ever Baltimore Ceasefire weekend showed that there has been only a slight decrease (4.2% decrease) in total number of homicides since Baltimore Ceasefire 365 was introduced. This shows that the impact of the Ceasefire weekends is fairly limited to just those weekends, and there isnt a larger ripple effect.

Baltimore Ceasefire weekends have demonstrated the potential of city-wide ceasefire calls in reducing gun-related murder counts. To judge whether the effectiveness of the policy in Baltimore can be similarly achieved in Boston, we need to understand differences between the two cities. Bostons gun-related homicide rate is lower than Baltimores and has been held steady over the past four years, but the gun murder rate of 8.3 deaths per 100,000 total population in 2017, is still higher than the national average rate of 4.6 deaths per 100,000 total population [1], signifying that there is still room for improvement. In comparing gun-related homicides between the two cities, one noticeable difference was the distribution of homicides over the week. In Baltimore, homicides are distributed more evenly over the week, with the worst weekday contributing to 16.2% of total homicides and the safest weekday contributing to 12.4%. In Boston, 25.4% of homicides occur on Saturdays, which is a substantially higher proportion compared to other weekdays. As a result, I would suggest targeting only Saturdays to begin with. Baltimore currently hosts quarterly Ceasefire weekends that last for 3 days each, meaning the ceasefire call is in effect 12 days a year. In Boston, if we choose to make ceasefire calls on Saturdays only, we can increase the frequency of the calls to once every month, and this will similarly add up to 12 days a year. I recognize that there are other factors that should be taken into consideration such as demographics (e.g.race, annual income, eduation level) and the nature of homicides (e.g.who commited the crime and for what reason), but with the current data involving only one region (i.e.Baltimore), it will be hard to improve on my current prediction of how successful the policy would work in a different region even if I have more information on the differences between the two regions. It will perhaps be useful to look into whether there have been any similar ceasefire programs implemented in other regions beyond Baltimore to better understand how ceasefire programs will function in regions with varying demographics and crime statistics. If you know of any such programs and are interested in further exploring the different programs, let me know, and I can perform a follow-up analysis if needed.

In addition, if we hope to implement such a policy, it is also important to consider the resources required to support and maintain the Ceasefire policy. Baltimore Ceasefire 365 was started by an organizing squad of six members who continue to serve at the core of the program. More people have joined in on the movement by applying to become ambassadors or being involved in volunteer work. Funding is provided by donations from the public, which totaled $29,906 this past year. Money raised from donations are used for producing outreach materials, and supporting families who lose loved ones to violence during ceasefire weekends. The labor and financial standards to implement a Ceasefire program do not seem to be high, so the question then lies in whether there is enough interest from Boston residents to run such a program. Perhaps a good solution would be to first spread the idea of Ceasefire Saturdays on social media to gauge how much interest there is from the public. If Boston residents are passionate about the subject, then I would suggest following through with the program, which may prove valuable in the years to come.
